super fast, but also very moody and

00:02:12.030 --> 00:02:16.500
volatile, meaning it forgets everything
the moment the power goes off.

00:02:16.980 --> 00:02:20.280
The best examples are ram
or random access memory.

00:02:20.695 --> 00:02:24.445
Which is used for temporary storage
of programs and data that are

00:02:24.445 --> 00:02:29.545
currently active, and then there
is ROM or read only memory, which

00:02:29.545 --> 00:02:33.144
stores permanent instructions,
like how to boot up the computer.

00:02:33.475 --> 00:02:37.734
It's non-volatile, so it remembers
everything even without power.

00:02:38.394 --> 00:02:42.234
Then comes the secondary memory,
also called auxiliary storage.

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:47.800
